message: “Greatest” is too subjective a term. More neutral language added in line with Wikipedia’s neutrality rules.
/* Status */Good point Betty Logan. I’ve clarified my comment.
/* Status */Content added on Hendry’s 36 ranking titles
/* World Champion and World Number One (1989–1999) */Content clarified
/* Neutrality violation on Stephen Hendry article */
“Greatest” is too subjective a term. “One of the most successful” is more appropriately neutral and consistent with the Stephen Hendry page.
/* World Champion and World Number One (1989–1999) */1989/1990 is a snooker season not a year!
/* World Champion and World Number One (1989–1999) */How to wind up Lee Vilenski...
/* Status */New source/content added. No other content changed. More than happy to discuss.
/* Status */Only sound and reliable references please
Not sure what you disagree with on this section?

/* Status */Can we please only include sound references and opinions from respected sources. An opinion from a single and relatively unknown journalist does not constitute a sound reference or respected source.
The wording on Hendry’s status has been replicated with that used in O’Sullivan’s page.
“According to World Snooker” is their opinion. Therefore the statement is factually changed and should not be changed.
Clarified status according to World Snooker

/* Reference to “greatest” in Stephen Hendry page */ new section
Please engage with talk page Lee rather than editing.

Betty Logan please see the talk page. I have no association with other editors, I am merely a snooker fan who is observing disruption between two pages of great importance to the promotion of the sport. I do not wish to push a particular agenda or enter into an edit war.

I don’t want to get into an edit war like the other editors and ask that you don’t attack my positive motives. I stand by my view that there should be consistency between both Hendry and O’Sullivan pages. If you disagree please edit the O’Sullivan page.

I agree there should be consistency between the O’Sullivan and Hendry pages. Alwaysrightman appears to have recently tried to amend both pages to create consistency, albeit he hasn’t gone about it in a diplomatic way at all.
